Appendices: Samples of Contemporary German-Language Novels in Translation -- tA: Vladimir Vertlib, Das besondere Gedächtnis der Rosa Masur: Chapter 16 -- tB: Clemens Meyer, Als wir träumten: Little Racer -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPresents fifteen new German-language novelists and a close reading of an exemplary work of each for academics and the general reader alike.After the international success in the 1990s of authors such as Bernhard Schlink, Marcel Beyer, and Thomas Brussig, an impressive number of new German-language novelists are making a significant impact. Some, like Karen Duve, Daniel Kehlmann, and Sasa Stanisic, have achieved international recognition; some, like Julia Franck, have won major prizes; others, like Clemens Meyer, Alina Bronsky, and Ilja Trojanow, are truly "emerging authors" who have begun toattract attention. Between them they represent a range of literatures in German, from women's writing to minority writing (from Turkish immigrants and Eastern Europe), to "pop literature" and perspectives on the former GDR and onGermany's Nazi past. This volume devotes individual essays to fifteen such writers, examining in detail a major work of each. Translated excerpts from works by Vladimir Vertlib and Clemens Meyer round out the book, which willbe of interest not only to academics and students of English and Comparative Literature in the UK, the US, and beyond, but also to the general reader, for whom titles of texts and "ations are translated. Contributors: Lyn Marven, Stuart Taberner, Anke S. Biendarra, Stephen Brockmann, Rebecca Braun, Frauke Matthes, Brigid Haines, Julian Preece, Emily Jeremiah, Valerie Heffernan, Barbara Mennel, Heike Bartel, Kate Roy, Andrew Plowman, Sonja E.Klocke, Jamie Lee Searle, Katy Derbyshire. Lyn Marven is a Lecturer in German at the University of Liverpool. Stuart Taberner is Professor of Contemporary German Literature, Culture, and Society at the University of Leeds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman fictionxHistory and criticismy21st century. 0aGerman fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman fictiony21st century. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAlina Bronsky.  aClemens Meyer.  aDaniel Kehlmann.  aFormer GDR.  aGerman Literature.  aGerman-Language Novelists.  aIlja Trojanow.  aJulia Franck.  aKaren Duve.  aPop Literature.  aSasa Stanisic.1 aBartel, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiendarra, Anke S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrockmann, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaines, Brigid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeffernan, Valerie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeremiah, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlocke, Sonja E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlocke, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarven, Lyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarven, Lyn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatthes, Frauke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMennel, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlowman, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreece, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g